@page "/about"

<PageTitle>About Starforged Atlas</PageTitle>

<section class="about-page">
    <header class="about-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
        <h1>Starforged Atlas is a modern RPG sector atlas built from the classic StarWin sector tools.</h1>
        <p>
            This application is being built to preserve and extend the data that StarWin could generate and browse:
            star systems, worlds, moons, colonies, alien races, empires, military profiles, civilization history,
            GURPS-ready campaign material, and eventually slip map data in the same project.
        </p>
    </header>

    <section class="about-grid">
        <article class="detail-panel">
            <span class="panel-kicker">Purpose</span>
            <h2>What this app is</h2>
            <p>
                Starforged Atlas is not a pixel-for-pixel clone of the original desktop interface. It is a domain-first
                .NET and Blazor application designed to display the same kinds of information in a clearer, searchable,
                database-backed website.
            </p>
            <p>
                The current development version can browse seeded sectors, systems, worlds, colonies, races, and empires.
                The project direction is to support importing StarWin 2 data and combine it with the Slip Map tool.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="detail-panel">
            <span class="panel-kicker">Original work</span>
            <h2>StarWin attribution</h2>
            <p>
                The original StarWin application was <strong>Star Generator for Windows</strong>. The legacy source
                included with this repository identifies the original author as <strong>Aina Rasolomalala</strong>,
                with copyright years <strong>1996-2001</strong>.
            </p>
            <p>
                This new application is a separate modernization effort that uses the original StarWin behavior and
                file formats as reference material while building a new domain model, persistence layer, and web UI.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="detail-panel">
            <span class="panel-kicker">Architecture</span>
            <h2>How it is being rebuilt</h2>
            <dl class="data-list">
                <div><dt>Domain</dt><dd>Star map, civilization, military, legacy import models</dd></div>
                <div><dt>Application</dt><dd>Browsing and search contracts</dd></div>
                <div><dt>Infrastructure</dt><dd>SQL LocalDB, EF Core, migrations, seed data</dd></div>
                <div><dt>Web</dt><dd>Blazor presentation and navigation</dd></div>
            </dl>
        </article>
    </section>
</section>
